2026-03-02 | Minimum Swaps to Make Grid Valid

	Question
Given grid[][],
return the minimum number of adjacent row swaps
required to make the grid valid,
or return -1 if impossible.

	Approach
1.	Key Observation:
	For row i to be placed at position i,
	it must have at least:
			(n − i − 1) trailing zeros.
2.	Precompute:
	For each row,
	count trailing zeros.
3.	Greedy Strategy:
	For each row position i:
		Find the first row j ≥ i
		with trailingZeros[j] ≥ (n − i − 1).
	4.	If no such row exists → return -1.
	5.	Otherwise:
		Bring row j up to position i
		using adjacent swaps.
		Add (j − i) to total swaps.
		Shift rows accordingly.
6.	Time Complexity:
		O(n²)
7.	Space Complexity:
		O(n)

	Solution

class Solution {
public:
    int minSwaps(vector<vector<int>>& grid) {
        int n = grid.size();
        vector<int> trailing(n);

        // Count trailing zeros for each row
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            int count = 0;
            for (int j = n - 1; j >= 0 && grid[i][j] == 0; j--) {
                count++;
            }
            trailing[i] = count;
        }

        int swaps = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            int required = n - i - 1;
            int j = i;

            while (j < n && trailing[j] < required)
                j++;

            if (j == n)
                return -1;

            while (j > i) {
                swap(trailing[j], trailing[j - 1]);
                swaps++;
                j--;
            }
        }

        return swaps;
    }
};

	Key Insight
Each row i must have enough trailing zeros
to ensure zeros above the diagonal.
Greedily pulling the nearest valid row upward
minimizes the number of adjacent swaps.
